observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Health Office, the Human Resource Management Office, and other concerned offices to submit the following documents:
The list of public health workers, including Barangay Health Workers, determined and approved by the Local Health Board;
Specific authority from the head of the agency to the claimants to physically report and respond to the public health emergency during the state of national emergency indicating therein the assigned work stations/health facilities for COVID-19, the prescribed official working hours, and their duties and responsibilities;
Certification attesting to the truthfulness of the contents of the report and adequate consent for sharing of data obtained from the personnel involved. The certification must be signed by the head of the human resource or personnel division and the head of the health facility, clearly indicating his/her designation or position; and,
Accomplishment Reports show that the claimants have provided direct treatment and support care to COVID-19 patients.

We recommended that Management:
Submit justification on the delayed submission of awarded contracts and POs to the office of the auditor, in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009;
Direct the personnel in-charge to furnish the Office of the Auditor with copies of the Contracts and POs together with its supporting documents within the prescribed period as required under COA Circular No. 2009-001;
Impose disciplinary action against defaulting personnel for any unjustified failure to comply with the requirements as provided in Section 4.1, COA Circular No. 2009-001.

We recommended that Management shall:

(a)	Direct the responsible officials/
implementing unit of the LGU that they shall coordinate with the community and private sectors in their locality, where applicable—to achieve effective and synchronized planning and implementation of any similar project in the future;

(b)	Carry out detailed engineering to ensure issues on road right-of-way and project viability are properly addressed during the feasibility or preliminary engineering studies;

c)	Conduct an inventory of work accomplished by the contractor and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay; and

(d)	Require the contractor to engage the catch-up program in order to fast track the completion of the project to avoid rescindment of contract as stipulated in Section 68 of RA 9184.

We recommended that management to:

(a)	Instruct the designated personnel of the school to discontinue the issuance of personalized Acknowledgement Receipts upon receipt of any other fees received from students and have it issued with authorized official receipt, preferably AF 51. Said collection shall be duly accounted and held as under Trust Liability and must be solely spent for the specific purpose for which it was created; 

(b)	Direct the policy-making body to revisit their existing policies and procedures, or install appropriate controls whenever necessary for the imposition and collection of additional school fees; it must also ensure those policies and guidelines must be well-defined and adequately communicated in clear and specific terms with written authority from its school Board of Trustees, subject to the prevailing laws and regulations.

We recommended the following courses of action: 

a. Direct the assigned personnel of the local college to stop the practice of demanding any additional fees unless prior approval by the Board of Trustees is secured;

b. Personnel in charge of the school shall consider the minimum requirements under R.A. No. 9184 as well as other applicable accounting and auditing rules and regulations in processing disbursement of funds pertaining to any of its procurement undertakings.

We recommended to the Management the following courses of actions:

1. Stop the operation of the present CD and prioritize the acquisition and utilization of a land suitable for the operation and management of waste to sustain the effective implementation of the Solid Waste Management Plan of the agency.

2. To conduct periodic public information and education campaign, through the Local Solid Waste Management Board, to encourage social awareness in the implementation of the Solid Waste Management Plan of the Local Government Unit to avoid environmental concerns and health issues in the future.

3. To develop strategies in achieving and implementing the minimum requirements of maintaining a CD.

4. To encourage the Barangays to activate the LSWMB to perform its functions and responsibilities as provided for in Section 6, Rule VI of the Act, to wit:

a.) Formulate solid waste management program consistent with city/ municipality plan;
b.) Segregation and collection of biodegradable, compostable, reusable wastes; 
c.) Establish materials recovery facility;
d.) Allocate barangay funds; look for sources of funds;
e.) Organize core coordinators;
f.) Submit monthly report to city or municipality

5. Strict implementation of the LSWMB on the operation of MRF, particularly on the following activities:

a.) Proper segregation of waste;
b.) The incessant utilization of MRF to minimize the volume of  wastes to be transported for disposal;
c.) The recording of waste received and its disposal.

Recommendations:
We recommended that Management shall:
Direct the responsible officials/implementing unit of the LGU that they shall coordinate with the community and private sectors in their locality, where applicable—to achieve effective and synchronized planning and implementation of any similar project in the future;
Carry out detailed engineering to ensure issues on road right-of-way and project viability are properly addressed during the feasibility or preliminary engineering studies;
Conduct an inventory of work accomplished by the contractor and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay; and
Require the contractor to engage the catch-up program in order to fast track the completion of the project to avoid rescindment of contract as stipulated in Section 68 of RA 9184.

